hey group, 
I&#39;m having a terrible time searching the space for solving a cross
product. 

Fitness is measured by giving it six inputs, one for x,y and z for each
input vector, and then measuring the absolute error of each of the three
output components. 

Every individual is tested on two different cross products every
generation. 

Every some number of generations ( I call ticks ) the cross product
inputs are randomly generated, and the new correct cross product
calculated. 

I limited the network size to 20 neurons, as I figure more than this
would be bloat.

I&#39;ve been plotting best fitness and average fitness, and it doesn&#39;t look
like it will ever converge on a solution (have run 4000 generations, pop
size 128). The algorithm does it&#39;s thing before I change the inputs,
where the error starts off big, then gets small on an asymptotic curve,
but it exactly the same way, over and over, every time I change the
inputs. The average fitness looks similar, but is generally moving down
from bad to worse. 
I think this should be a straight forward domain, as the math is only
six calculations. What am I doing wrong? 

chad 

